ype":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Keep this modest. If one `if (error)` branch is clearer, use the branch."},"302":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"303":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"304":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"305":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"306":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"For async streams or generators, reach for `yieldless/iterable` instead of materializing everything first."},"307":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"308":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"309":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a firm time budget, derive one signal and pass it through the whole call chain."},"310":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you are calling HTTP JSON APIs, `yieldless/fetch` combines the same ideas:"},"311":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you need to wait for eventual consistency, use `poll()` instead of hand-writing timers."},"312":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"The package ships helpers for common backend boundaries and production pressure:"},"313":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/env` validates startup configuration"},"314":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/fetch` wraps HTTP status, JSON parsing, and deadlines"},"315":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schema` keeps validators in tuple form"},"316":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple handlers into HTTP responses"},"317":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/ipc` preserves tuple results across Electron IPC"},"318":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps filesystem and child-process work"},"319":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/event` waits for one event with cleanup and abort support"},"320":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schedule` builds reusable retry and repeat policies"},"321":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects shared capacity with semaphores and rate limits"},"322":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/queue` and `yieldless/pubsub` coordinate in-process workers and subscribers"},"323":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/cache` keeps successful read-through loads fresh for a TTL"},"324":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby keyed reads into ordered batches"},"325":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/breaker` backs off dependencies that are already failing"},"326":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/singleflight` deduplicates duplicate in-flight work"},"327":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-50","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/test` makes promises, clocks, and abort signals deterministic in tests"},"328":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-51","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Examples when you want copy-pasteable small patterns and a few larger compositions."},"329":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-52","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Module Selection when you are deciding which helper fits a specific problem."},"330":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-53","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Design Rules before you spread the tuple style across a large codebase."},"331":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-54","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Do and Don't if you are moving a team onto the library and want the conventions to stay sharp."},"332":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Use the reference section when you already know what module you need."},"333":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-56","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Most UI and domain code wants ordinary values or ordinary state. Convert at the boundary."},"334":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"page","content":"Bounded Batch Work","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work"},"335":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"336":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"337":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"338":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"Good variation: stream the input"},"339":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"Avoid: unbounded fan-out"},"340":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"341":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"342":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"343":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"344":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"345":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"346":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"If repositories come from an async source, use `yieldless/iterable` instead of building a large array first."},"347":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"That can launch dozens or hundreds of subprocesses. Use `mapLimit()` or `mapAsyncLimit()` so the user’s machine stays responsive."},"348":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"page","content":"Checkout Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow"},"349":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"A customer checkout example with validation, inventory reads, payment resilience, rate limits, and receipt jobs."},"350":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"351":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#checkout-service","content":"Checkout service"},"352":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#receipt-worker","content":"Receipt worker"},"353":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Why this is a good fit"},"354":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#avoid-hiding-business-rules-behind-a-generic-pipeline","content":"Avoid: hiding business rules behind a generic pipeline"},"355":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"Checkout is a good Yieldless fit because it crosses several failure-heavy boundaries without needing a framework runtime: user input, inventory reads, payment APIs, rate limits, and background receipts."},"356":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"This recipe keeps those boundaries explicit. The service code still reads like ordinary TypeScript, but the painful edges return tuples and accept cancellation."},"357":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/router` turns the tuple service into an HTTP response"},"358":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates checkout input"},"359":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/cache` and `yieldless/batcher` keep inventory reads efficient"},"360":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects a payment API quota"},"361":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/breaker` fails fast while the payment provider is unhealthy"},"362":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/queue` stores receipt work for a local worker"},"363":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps remote API calls in tuple form"},"364":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Cart validation returns a normal HTTP validation response."},"365":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Inventory reads batch together and cache briefly, which helps busy product pages."},"366":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Payment quota is explicit before the payment call."},"367":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"The circuit breaker stops a payment outage from becoming a retry storm."},"368":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Receipt delivery is queued so checkout can finish without waiting on email."},"369":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#avoid-hiding-business-rules-behind-a-generic-pipeline","content":"That hides the parts reviewers most need to see: stock checks, idempotency, payment error handling, and what happens after the customer pays."},"370":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"page","content":"Command Runner","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner"},"371":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"Run local tools with live logs, deadlines, output limits, cancellation, and safe argument boundaries."},"372":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#command-runner-service","content":"Command runner service"},"373":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#showing-progress-in-a-ui","content":"Showing progress in a UI"},"374":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#returning-a-useful-result","content":"Returning a useful result"},"375":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Good"},"376":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"377":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"Many products eventually need to run a local tool: a project build, a formatter, a video transcode, a document converter, or a test command. The hard part is rarely starting the process. The hard part is keeping the UI responsive, stopping cleanly when the user cancels, and returning enough detail to explain what happened."},"378":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"This recipe builds a small command runner for developer tools and desktop apps."},"379":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#command-runner-service","content":"`runScript()` accepts the script name as an argument, so Node keeps argument boundaries intact. `runTrustedPipeline()` uses a shell command string because the `&&` syntax is intentionally shell-specific and controlled by the application."},"380":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#showing-progress-in-a-ui","content":"The UI does not need to know how the process is spawned. It subscribes to ordinary events and owns cancellation through one `AbortController`."},"381":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#returning-a-useful-result","content":"The command result includes the command, args, working directory, duration, stdout, stderr, exit code, and signal. That makes audit logs and support screens possible without reparsing the terminal transcript."},"382":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Use `runCommandSafe(file, args)` when any part of the command came from a user, a project setting, or a database row."},"383":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Use `runShellCommandSafe()` for trusted shell syntax that is easier to read as one command."},"384":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Do not put user-controlled values into a shell command string."},"385":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Use separate arguments instead. It reads a little longer, but it avoids shell injection and quoting edge cases."},"386":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"page","content":"Customer Import","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import"},"387":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"Import a customer CSV with validation, bounded concurrency, duplicate checks, progress events, and polite API calls."},"388":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#import-service","content":"Import service"},"389":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#streaming-progress-to-a-ui","content":"Streaming progress to a UI"},"390":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Why this is a good fit"},"391":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#avoid-one-promise-per-row","content":"Avoid: one promise per row"},"392":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"Bulk imports are familiar to almost every product team. They look simple until a customer uploads a file with thousands of rows, duplicate emails, invalid data, and a slow CRM integration."},"393":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"This recipe keeps the import understandable:"},"394":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"validate each row as data"},"395":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"check duplicates in batches"},"396":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"limit outbound CRM calls"},"397":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"publish progress as rows complete"},"398":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"stop cleanly when the user cancels"},"399":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#streaming-progress-to-a-ui","content":"The UI does not need to know about batching, rate limiting, or CRM failures. It gets ordinary domain events."},"400":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Invalid rows become skipped rows instead of crashing the whole import."},"401":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Duplicate checks batch together instead of hitting the database once per row."},"402":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"CRM calls run with bounded concurrency and a rate limit."},"403":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"A single `AbortSignal` lets the user cancel the import from the UI."},"404":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Progress is an async subscription, so it works for web sockets, server-sent events, Electron IPC, or tests."},"405":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#avoid-one-promise-per-row","content":"That pattern looks tidy until a customer uploads 20,000 rows. Use `mapLimit()` when the input is customer-sized."},"406":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"407":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"408":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"409":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"410":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"411":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"412":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"413":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"414":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"415":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"416":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"417":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"418":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"419":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"420":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate status reads if several panels can request the same repository at once."},"421":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Wait for one app or window event with cleanup."},"422":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Do not expose arbitrary IPC channels to the renderer."},"423":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Build a small preload bridge with `createIpcBridge()` or `createAbortableIpcBridge()` so the renderer only sees the operations it is allowed to call."},"424":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"425":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"426":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"427":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"428":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"429":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"430":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"431":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"432":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"433":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"434":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"435":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"436":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Use tuples while you are still doing failure-heavy work: GitHub API calls, local Git reads, diff parsing, cache reads, IPC boundaries."},"437":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Once the renderer receives the result, fold it into ordinary screen state and move on."},"438":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"The important thing here is not the exact helper list. It is the layering:"},"439":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/error` keeps the boundary readable with `ok()` and `err()`."},"440":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/all` loads the PR payload in parallel."},"441":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/task` gives the whole request one shared cancellation signal."},"442":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/node` keeps Git subprocess failures in the same tuple contract."},"443":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"This is the point where Yieldless should usually stop being the dominant shape."},"444":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"That keeps the renderer normal. Components render `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, or `error`. They do not need to carry `[error, value]` through every prop."},"445":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Pull-request work crosses many noisy boundaries: GitHub HTTP, local Git, caches, and Electron IPC."},"446":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Cancellation matters because users jump between PRs quickly and the old load should stop being important."},"447":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"The renderer wants stable view state, not a low-level transport shape."},"448":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate duplicate PR loads while a user is switching tabs or refreshing panels."},"449":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Use bounded iterable work when processing many files in a diff."},"450":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Do not keep tuples as your component model."},"451":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Fold the tuple once into `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, and `error` state. UI code should speak in screen states."},"452":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Use Yieldless in the main process and preload boundary."},"453":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Convert tuples into domain state at the renderer edge."},"454":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Do not force tuple results deep into component trees."},"455":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"page","content":"Repository Indexer","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer"},"456":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"A larger example that combines queues, pub/sub, caching, batching, limits, retries, task groups, and Node subprocesses."},"457":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#the-indexer","content":"The indexer"},"458":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"Using it from a route or action"},"459":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Why this is easier to operate"},"460":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#smaller-variations","content":"Smaller variations"},"461":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"Process a fixed list without a long-running queue"},"462":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"Keep only the cache and batcher"},"463":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"Add a circuit breaker to an optional dependency"},"464":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"Avoid: hiding the pipeline inside a generic worker framework"},"465":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"This recipe shows a realistic in-process worker pipeline: a user selects repositories, the app indexes them, progress is streamed to the UI, remote metadata is cached, owner lookups are batched, and local Git subprocesses stay bounded."},"466":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"The point is not to build a new runtime. The point is to keep the moving parts visible:"},"467":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/queue` accepts work with backpressure"},"468":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/pubsub` broadcasts progress"},"469":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/task` runs workers under one cancellation signal"},"470":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects API quota and local subprocess capacity"},"471":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/cache` avoids repeated metadata reads"},"472":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby owner lookups"},"473":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient remote failures"},"474":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps remote calls in tuple form"},"475":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps local Git commands as tuples"},"476":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"In a real UI, the progress subscription often lives in a websocket, server-sent events stream, or Electron IPC handler. The shape stays the same: subscribe, render events, and abort when the user leaves."},"477":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"The queue is bounded, so user-selected work cannot grow memory forever."},"478":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Worker count is explicit, so local Git subprocesses stay polite."},"479":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"API quota waits happen before remote calls, not after the upstream complains."},"480":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Metadata reads are cached, but failed reads are not stored."},"481":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Owner lookups batch together while still returning one result per job."},"482":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Retry policy sits around the flaky remote read, not around the whole pipeline."},"483":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Progress is just an async subscription, so it can feed logs, UI, or tests."},"484":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"If you already have the whole list and do not need progress fanout, `mapLimit()` is smaller."},"485":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"If the pipeline is overkill, keep the read model helpers."},"486":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-30","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"If indexing can continue without feature flags or recommendations, wrap that optional remote call with a circuit breaker and use a fallback when it is open."},"487":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-31","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"That looks shorter, but the operational choices disappear. Yieldless works best when the important limits remain close to the work they protect."},"488":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"page","content":"Resilient Service Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow"},"489":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"A practical backend flow that combines tuples, retries, validation, routing, and cancellation."},"490":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"491":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#route-handler","content":"Route handler"},"492":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Why this holds up well in production"},"493":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"Good variation: add a remote dependency"},"494":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"Avoid: retrying the whole handler"},"495":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Rules worth keeping"},"496":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, 